**TL;DR: The One Rule That Governs Every Princess Cut Solitaire Purchase**

A princess cut diamond has four 90-degree corners. These corners are structural vulnerabilities — the crystal lattice terminates at a sharp angle with no natural cleavage protection. Without a V-tip prong on each corner, daily wear subjects those corners to lateral impact, abrasion from fabric and other surfaces, and micro-fracture accumulation. The result is not eventual possible damage — it is **eventual guaranteed damage** in active-wear conditions.

Every solitaire setting in this guide is evaluated for V-prong compatibility. This is the only structural criterion that matters for a princess cut solitaire.

---

## What Is the Corner Chip Risk?

The Corner Chip Risk is the name for a structural fact about princess cut diamonds that most jewelers understate and most buyers discover after purchase.

**The physics:**
- Princess cut corners terminate at approximately 90 degrees with no additional facet to distribute impact energy
- Diamond is the hardest natural substance (Mohs 10) but is not immune to cleavage — it cleaves readily along its crystal planes
- The 90-degree corner of a princess cut aligns closely with a natural diamond cleavage direction
- Daily wear (opening car doors, gripping gym equipment, doing dishes, typing) delivers repeated micro-impacts to the corner region
- Without prong protection, corner fractures begin microscopically and propagate over months to years into visible chips

**The numbers:**
- Unprotected princess corners at 1ct: estimated 50–60% visible chipping risk within 5 years of daily wear
- V-prong protected: chip risk reduces to <5%
- Bezel protected: chip risk reduces to <1%

**What V-prong means:** A V-tip prong (also called a V-prong or V-tip) has a notched V-shape at its contact point with the diamond, cradling the corner inside the V-notch. This shields the corner from lateral impact while maintaining the visual sharpness of the corner from above.

