## Which Solitaire Settings Have the Corner Chip Problem?

![14K White Gold Six-Prong Knife Edge Solitaire — this 6-prong style is designed for round brilliants, not princess cuts](/images/princess-cut-solitaire-ring-six-prong-white-gold.avif)

**Settings to avoid for princess cut:**

| Setting Type | Problem |
|---|---|
| Six-prong round head | Designed for round brilliants — prongs don't align to princess corners |
| Tension setting | Zero corner protection — stone held by pressure only |
| Channel-set head | Encircles stone but leaves corners exposed at channel edges |
| Standard round 4-prong | Prongs contact facets, not corners — corners remain unprotected |
| Shared-prong pavé (as primary) | Pavé prongs on band only — center corners unprotected |

**The distinction:** Four-prong solitaire heads designed for princess cut place prongs AT the four corners. Six-prong heads designed for round brilliants place prongs at six equal intervals around the girdle — three of these six prongs land on the flat facets between corners, not at the corners themselves. This leaves 2 corners unprotected.

Always confirm: "Does this setting have four corner V-tip prongs for the princess cut center stone?" Blue Nile customer service will confirm via live chat.

