## FAQ

### What is a V-prong setting for princess cut?
A V-tip prong has a notched V-shape at its tip that cradles the 90-degree corner of a princess diamond inside the V-notch. This shields the corner from lateral impact. Distinguish from a standard round prong, which contacts the diamond's facets but leaves the corners unprotected.

### Can I put a princess cut diamond in any solitaire setting?
No. Only solitaire settings with heads designed for princess cut center stones (four corner prongs) are appropriate. Settings with six-prong round heads or tension settings expose the corners and should not be used with princess cut diamonds.

### How often do princess cut corners chip?
Without V-prong protection, approximately 50–60% of princess cuts in daily wear settings show corner damage within 5 years based on jeweler repair estimates. With V-prong protection, the rate drops below 5%.

### Is a princess cut solitaire classic or modern?
Both. The princess cut peaked in popularity in the 2000s and has declined since, but a clean platinum solitaire with a princess center is a timeless aesthetic. It reads more modern and geometric than round solitaires, which suits buyers who prefer clean lines over romanticized curves.

### What is the cheapest complete princess cut solitaire ring?
Split Shank Claw Solitaire in 14K Rose Gold (JA) at $790 + GIA 1ct G-VS2 at $2,212 = **$3,002 total**. This is the minimum complete ring on Blue Nile with a certified GIA 1ct stone.

